"**Lady Jane** " is a song by the English [rock](/wiki/Rock_music "Rock
music") [band](/wiki/Musical_ensemble "Musical ensemble"), [The Rolling
Stones](/wiki/The_Rolling_Stones "The Rolling Stones"), penned by the group's
[songwriting duo](/wiki/Jagger/Richards "Jagger/Richards") of [Mick
Jagger](/wiki/Mick_Jagger "Mick Jagger") and [Keith
Richards](/wiki/Keith_Richards "Keith Richards"), and initially included on
their [album](/wiki/Album "Album"),
_[Aftermath](/wiki/Aftermath_\(The_Rolling_Stones_album\) "Aftermath \(The
Rolling Stones album\)")_ , which was released on 12 April 1966.[4] It
showcased [Brian Jones](/wiki/Brian_Jones "Brian Jones")'s instrumental
incorporation of [baroque rock](/wiki/Baroque_rock "Baroque rock") as it was
beginning to be introduced, and became influential in originating the musical
style later known as [world music](/wiki/World_music "World music").[5] The
song was released as the [B-side](/wiki/B-side "B-side") to "[Mother's Little
Helper](/wiki/Mother%27s_Little_Helper "Mother's Little Helper")"
[single](/wiki/Single_\(music\) "Single \(music\)") on 2 July 1966, and
managed to chart in the [_Billboard_ Hot 100](/wiki/Billboard_Hot_100
"Billboard Hot 100"), peaking at number 24.[6]

## History[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Lady_Jane_\(song\)&action=edit&section=1
"Edit section: History")]

###
Composition[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Lady_Jane_\(song\)&action=edit&section=2
"Edit section: Composition")]

The song was written at a milestone in [The Rolling
Stones](/wiki/The_Rolling_Stones "The Rolling Stones") recording career that
saw the [musical collaboration](/wiki/Jagger/Richards "Jagger/Richards") of
[Mick Jagger](/wiki/Mick_Jagger "Mick Jagger"),and [Keith
Richards](/wiki/Keith_Richards "Keith Richards") emerge as the group's chief
songwriters. On the band's previous album, _[Out of Our
Heads](/wiki/Out_of_Our_Heads "Out of Our Heads")_ , the duo shared writing
credits on just three tracks. On
_[Aftermath](/wiki/Aftermath_\(The_Rolling_Stones_album\) "Aftermath \(The
Rolling Stones album\)")_ , however, the two were credited together on every
track, making it the first album to be composed solely of original band
material.[7] It was also during this period [Brian Jones](/wiki/Brian_Jones
"Brian Jones"), despite losing control of the band's output, was integrating
different instruments into the group's repertoire. Joe S. Harrington has noted
that [The Beatles](/wiki/The_Beatles "The Beatles")'
[harpsichord](/wiki/Harpsichord "Harpsichord") arrangement featured on the
song "[In My Life](/wiki/In_My_Life "In My Life")", in 1965, opened
considerations for Jones to include baroque rock instrumentals.[5]

"Lady Jane" was written and composed by Jagger in early 1966 after reading the
then controversial book _[Lady Chatterley's
Lover](/wiki/Lady_Chatterley%27s_Lover "Lady Chatterley's Lover")_, which uses
the term "Lady Jane" to mean [female genitalia](/wiki/Female_genitalia "Female
genitalia").[8] According to Jagger, "the names [in the song] are historical,
but it was really unconscious that they should fit together from the same
period."[9] At the time, it was widely thought that an inspiration for the
song was [Jane Ormsby-Gore](/w/index.php?title=Jane_Ormsby-
Gore&action=edit&redlink=1 "Jane Ormsby-Gore \(page does not exist\)"),
daughter of [David Ormsby-Gore](/wiki/David_Ormsby-Gore "David Ormsby-Gore"),
former British ambassador in Washington, who later married [Michael
Rainey](/wiki/Michael_Rainey "Michael Rainey"), founder of the Hung on You
boutique in [Chelsea](/wiki/Chelsea,_London "Chelsea, London") that was
frequented by the Stones.[10] Its most impactful development was by Jones, no
longer the principal musical force for the band, searching for methods to
improve upon The Rolling Stones' musical textures.[11] He expressed an
intrigue in incorporating culturally diverse instruments into the band's
music, investigating the [sitar](/wiki/Sitar "Sitar"),
[koto](/wiki/Koto_\(instrument\) "Koto \(instrument\)"),
[marimba](/wiki/Marimba "Marimba"), and testing electronics. In the press
Jones talked about applying the [Appalachian
dulcimer](/wiki/Appalachian_dulcimer "Appalachian dulcimer") into
compositions, although he seemed uncertain of the instrument, saying "It's an
old English instrument used at the beginning of the century". The dulcimer was
first brought to his attention in March 1966 when Jones began listening to
recordings of [Richard Fariña](/wiki/Richard_Fari%C3%B1a "Richard Fariña").
The influence of these recordings would manifest itself in _Aftermath_ , where
Jones performed with the dulcimer on two tracks, "I Am Waiting" and, more
distinctively, "Lady Jane". This later contributed to Jones's status as an
early pioneer in [world music](/wiki/World_music "World music"), and
effectively shifted the band from [blues rock](/wiki/Blues_rock "Blues rock")
to a versatile pop group.[12][13]

###
Recording[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Lady_Jane_\(song\)&action=edit&section=3
"Edit section: Recording")]

The master recording of "Lady Jane" was recorded from 6 to 9 March 1966, at
RCA Studios in Los Angeles, with [sound engineer](/wiki/Sound_engineer "Sound
engineer") [Dave Hassinger](/wiki/Dave_Hassinger "Dave Hassinger") guiding the
band through the process (despite [Andrew Loog
Oldham](/wiki/Andrew_Loog_Oldham "Andrew Loog Oldham") being credited as
producer).[14] Mark Brend has indicated that the influence of Fariña's
dulcimer playing can be clearly heard - most noticeably in Jones's recurring
counter-melody to a call and response with Jagger's [vocals](/wiki/Vocals
"Vocals"). Jones plays the instrument in the traditional style, with it placed
on his knees fretted with a biter and plucked with a quill.[12] In addition to
the striking dulcimer [motif](/wiki/Motif_\(music\) "Motif \(music\)"), "Lady
Jane" is also highlighted by [Jack Nitzche](/wiki/Jack_Nitzche "Jack
Nitzche")'s harpsichord accompaniment halfway through the song.[15] "Lady
Jane" also exhibits influences of [author](/wiki/Author "Author") [Geoffry
Chaucer](/wiki/Geoffry_Chaucer "Geoffry Chaucer"), particularly in Jagger's
comic vocal delivery and diction. To Richards, "Lady Jane is very Elizabethan.
There are a few places in England where people still speak that way, Chaucer
English".[15][16] The vocal melody is set in the [subtonic](/wiki/Subtonic
"Subtonic") range, rather than the conventional major seventh scale degree,
which presents a Renaissance-style modal. Although stylistically the two songs
have little in common, the modality connects the Eastern-melody and harmonies
of "Lady Jane" to "[Paint It Black](/wiki/Paint_It_Black "Paint It
Black")".[17]

## Release[[edit](/w/index.php?title=Lady_Jane_\(song\)&action=edit&section=4
"Edit section: Release")]

In the U.S., "Lady Jane" was the B-side to "[Mother's Little
Helper](/wiki/Mother%27s_Little_Helper "Mother's Little Helper")", but "Lady
Jane" reached number 24 on Billboard's Hot 100 singles chart. "Mother's Little
Helper" reached number eight, making the release one of the few singles with
both songs becoming hits in the US.[18]
